l":{"about 1215–1271":"circa 1215–1271","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1222–Female":"1222–Overleden","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1248–1304":"1248–1304","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1190":"1190","before 1238":"vóór 1238","Cir 1245":"1245","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","Cir 1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"circa 1215","1222":"1222","Inwardleigh, Devon, England":"Inwardleigh, Devon, England","Shute, Axminster, Devon, England":"Axminster, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Shute, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Shute, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1215–1271":"about 1215–1271","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1222–Female":"1222–Deceased","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1248–1304":"1248–1304","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1190":"1190","before 1238":"before 1238","Cir 1245":"1245","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","Cir 1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"about 1215","1222":"1222","Inwardleigh, Devon, England":"Inwardleigh, Devon, England","Shute, Axminster, Devon, England":"Axminster, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Shute, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Shute, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shute","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of several places called with Middle English <i>shute</i>, Old English <i>scīete</i> ‘projecting piece of land’ (often in the corner of a parish), in particular those in Devon, which include Shute near Axminster, Shute in Kelly, Shute in Ugborough, Shute in Shobrooke, Shute Farm in Bishopsteignton, and Shewte in Bovey Tracy. Other sources of the surname may include Shute Farm in Longbridge Deverill and Shute Farm in Donhead Saint Mary (both Wiltshire).","In some cases also an Americanized form of Croatian and Slovenian <b>Šute</b>, and probably also of its cognate <b>Šutej</b> (see   Shutey  ). Compare   Shutte   and   Schutte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Shutes","meanings":["English: variant of   Shute  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Shutt","meanings":["English: variant of   Shute  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>schut(te)</i>, <i>schit(te)</i> ‘archer’ (Old English <i>scytta</i>, a derivative of <i>scēotan</i> ‘to shoot’). Compare   Shutter  .","Americanized form of German   Schutt   or   Schott  ."]},{"name":"Shutey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Americanized form of Croatian and Slovenian <b>Šutej</b>: nickname derived from Croatian (and possibly also Slovenian dialect) <i>šut</i> ‘without horns/ears’, also ‘mutilated, lame’, or perhaps from a derivative of Croatian <i>šutjeti</i> ‘to be silent’, Slovenian dialect <i>šut(l)ati</i> ‘to work silently’. Compare   Shute   and   Schutte  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":44,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de Shute was born about 1215, in Axminster, Devon, England as the son of Lucas de Shute. He married Roesia Coffin before 1238. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1271, in Inwardleigh, Devon, England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"about 1215–1271":"umbes 1215–1271","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1248–1304":"1248–1304","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1238":"enne 1238","Cir 1245":"1245","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","Cir 1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1222":"1222","Inwardleigh, Devon, England":"Inwardleigh, Devon, 